      {
        "scenario": "A: Fraud detection service down (503) for 5 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED FAILURE MODE: Every inbound payment request will call fraud service, get 503, likely after some wait or immediately depending on implementation. Without a circuit breaker, ALL 20 worker threads continue hammering the dead service. If the client retries on 503, requests pile up. If the service waits the full 2s timeout before failing, throughput drops to 10 req/s max (20 threads ÷ 2s). If it fails fast on 503, payments simply fail for 5 minutes with no degradation path. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE SURVIVES but ALL payments fail for 5 minutes. No cascading failure, but 100% payment failure rate. FIX: Add circuit breaker (3-failure threshold, 30s reset). Consider a fallback policy — e.g., allow low-risk payments to proceed without fraud check, or queue for async fraud review."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "B: Database connection pool exhaustion for 30 seconds",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED FAILURE MODE: This is the most dangerous scenario. Pool exhaustion means: (1) Fraud checks SUCCEED and consume 2s per request, (2) Stripe charges SUCCEED and money is collected, (3) DB write FAILS — transaction record is lost. You have taken the customer's money but have no record of it. With no connection retry, these payments are silently lost. Additionally, all 20 worker threads will block waiting for DB connections, causing complete service freeze — new requests queue up, health checks may fail, orchestrator may restart the pod, losing in-flight state. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE FAILS CRITICALLY. Money is collected without records. Potential data loss and financial reconciliation nightmare. FIX: (1) Reverse the order — reserve DB connection FIRST, before calling Stripe. (2) Add connection pool retry with backoff (3 attempts, 500ms/1s/2s). (3) Increase pool to at least match worker threads (20). (4) Implement outbox pattern — write intent to DB before charging Stripe."
