      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition from Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED FAILURE MODE: Requests to Stripe will hang for 10s (full timeout) then fail. Circuit breaker trips after 5 failures — that's 5 × 10s = 50 seconds of 5 threads blocked before breaker opens. During those 50s, 5 of 20 threads are consumed. After breaker opens, requests fail fast for 60s (reset window). At 60s, breaker goes half-open, one request tries Stripe, hangs for 10s, fails, breaker reopens. This cycle repeats: 60s closed → 10s probe → fail → reopen. Effectively, payments fail for the full 2 minutes plus recovery time. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE SURVIVES operationally. Circuit breaker prevents thread starvation after initial 50s degradation period. But the 50s slow-trip window is dangerous under high load — 5 threads blocked × 10s = significant capacity reduction. FIX: Reduce circuit breaker threshold to 3 failures. Add a shorter connect timeout (2s) separate from read timeout (10s) — network partitions will be detected in 2s instead of 10s. This reduces slow-trip window from 50s to 10s."
